<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="ch4-section-application-earth" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Application of a rotating reference frame to Earth</title>

    <p>
        While either side of <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality" text="type-global" />
        is equivalent to <m>\dfrac{D\vec{A}}{Dt}</m>,
        we are most interested in the expression on its right-hand side
        because we live on the rotating Earth and view atmospheric phenomena as we and the phenomena rotate along with the planet.
        Going forward, associate the rotating coordinate system with Earth by interpreting <m>\vec{\Omega}</m> as Earth's angular velocity,
        which is directed parallel to Earth's axis of rotation and points from the South Pole toward the North Pole.
        The associated angular speed is
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            \Omega = \frac{2\pi}{t_D} = 7.292 \times 10^{-5} \, \text{rad s}^{-1}
        </md>
    </p>
    
    <p>
        where <m>t_D = 86156.09</m> s is the length of a <term>sidereal day</term>,
        which is the time it takes for Earth to rotate once relative to the distant stars.
        (A sidereal day is slightly shorter than a <term>solar day</term>
        because Earth orbits the Sun as it rotates on its axis of rotation.)
    </p>

    <p>
        <m>\vec{A}</m> in <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality" text="type-global" /> is arbitrary,
        so we can replace it with any vector of interest.
        Let's replace <m>\vec{A}</m> with position vector <m>\vec{r}</m>
        that points from Earth's center to an air parcel of interest as it moves through Earth's atmosphere:
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-derivative-equality-position" number="yes">
            \left( \frac{D\vec{r}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}
            =
            \left( \frac{D\vec{r}}{Dt} \right)_{rot}
            + \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        As we reviewed in <xref ref="ch2-section-cartesian-coordinates" text="type-global" />,
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            \frac{D\vec{r}}{Dt} = \vec{u}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        Inserting this definition into <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality-position" text="type-global" /> produces
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-derivative-equality-velocity" number="yes">
            \vec{u}_{abs}
            =
            \vec{u}_{rot}
            +
            \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        <m>\vec{u}_{abs} = u_{abs} \, \hat{i}_{abs} + v_{abs} \, \hat{j}_{abs} + w_{abs} \, \hat{k}_{abs}</m>
        is the velocity of the air parcel measured relative to the inertial reference frame.
        According to <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality-velocity" text="type-global" />,
        <m>\vec{u}_{abs}</m> is equivalent to the velocity of the air parcel measured relative to the rotating reference frame
        <m>\vec{u}_{rot} = u_{rot} \, \hat{i}_{rot} + v_{rot} \, \hat{j}_{rot} + w_{rot} \, \hat{k}_{rot}</m>
        (i.e., the velocity of the air parcel relative to Earth, which is the wind)
        summed with the tangential velocity imparted to the air parcel by the rotation of the reference frame
        <m>\vec{u}_T = \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r}</m>
        (i.e., the velocity of the air parcel due to Earth's rotation).
        The relationship in <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality-velocity" text="type-global" /> could be written as
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-derivative-equality-velocity-relative" number="yes">
            \vec{u}_{air \, parcel/abs}
            =
            \vec{u}_{air \, parcel/rot}
            +
            \vec{u}_{rot/abs}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        to emphasize <m>\vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r}</m>
        is velocity caused by the rotation of the non-inertial coordinate system relative to the inertial coordinate system
        as well as to more clearly highlight the direct correspondence between the terms in
        <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality-velocity" text="type-global" />
        and the terms in <xref ref="eqn-relative-motion" text="type-global" />.
    </p>

    <p>
        Note <m>\vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r}</m> simply depends on the air parcel's position given by <m>\vec{r}</m>
        and not on its movement relative to Earth.
        This means <m>\vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r} \neq \vec{0}</m> whether or not the air parcel is moving relative to Earth.
        Consequently,
        even if the air parcel is stationary on Earth's surface or in its atmosphere, it will rotate along with Earth
        and therefore move through space.
    </p>

    <p>
        Now let's replace <m>\vec{A}</m> in <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality" text="type-global" />
        with <m>\vec{u}_{abs}</m> to produce a statement about the air parcel's acceleration.
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-derivative-equality-acceleration" number="yes">
            \left( \frac{D\vec{u}_{abs}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}
            =
            \left( \frac{D\vec{u}_{abs}}{Dt} \right)_{rot}
            + \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{u_{abs}}
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        We substitute <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality-velocity" text="type-global" />
        into the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-derivative-equality-acceleration" text="type-global" />
        and expand.
    </p>

    <p>
        <md>
            <mrow>
                \left( \frac{D\vec{u}_{abs}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}
                \amp =
                \left(
                    \frac{D \left( \vec{u}_{rot}
                    + \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r} \right) }{Dt}
                \right)_{rot}
                +
                \vec{\Omega} \times
                \left(
                    \vec{u}_{rot}
                    + \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r}
                \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
                \amp =
                \left(
                    \frac{D \vec{u}_{rot}}{Dt}
                \right)_{rot}
                +
                \vec{\Omega} \times
                \left(
                    \frac{D \vec{r}}{Dt}
                \right)_{rot}
                +
                \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{u}_{rot}
                +
                \vec{\Omega} \times \left( \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
                \amp =
                \left(
                    \frac{D \vec{u}_{rot}}{Dt}
                \right)_{rot}
                +
                \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{u}_{rot}
                +
                \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{u}_{rot}
                +
                \vec{\Omega} \times \left( \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r} \right)
            </mrow>
            <mrow xml:id="eqn-motion-vector-subscripts" number="yes">
                \amp =
                \left(
                    \frac{D \vec{u}_{rot}}{Dt}
                \right)_{rot}
                +
                2\vec{\Omega} \times \vec{u}_{rot}
                +
                \vec{\Omega} \times \left( \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r} \right)
            </mrow>
        </md>
    </p>

    <p>
        In most presentations of this derivation,
        the "rot" subscript usually is dropped after this point for brevity,
        and the left-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-motion-vector-subscripts" text="type-global" />
        usually is written <m>\left( \dfrac{D\vec{u}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}</m>
        and represents the acceleration of the air parcel relative to the inertial coordinate system.
        The first term on the right-hand side of <xref ref="eqn-motion-vector-subscripts" text="type-global" />,
        which now will be written <m>\dfrac{D\vec{u}}{Dt}</m>,
        is the acceleration of the air parcel relative to the rotating coordinate system,
        i.e., relative to Earth.
        Then we have
    </p>

    <p>
        <md xml:id="eqn-motion-vector" number="yes">
            \left( \frac{D\vec{u}}{Dt} \right)_{abs}
            =
            \frac{D\vec{u}}{Dt}
            + 2\vec{\Omega} \times \vec{u}
            + \vec{\Omega} \times \left( \vec{\Omega} \times \vec{r} \right)
        </md>
    </p>

</section>